  1. Explore the distribution of each of the x, y, and z variables in diamonds. What do you learn? Think about a diamond and how you might decide which dimension is the length, width, and depth.
fdiamonds <- filter(diamonds, z < 10 & y < 10 & x < 10)

ggplot(fdiamonds) +
  geom_density( aes( x = x ), color = "red") +
  geom_density( aes( x = y ), color = "blue") +
  geom_density( aes( x = z ), color = "green")

From the chart we can see that x and z variables are usually the same value, thats probably because a diamond has a circular shape if seen from above (probably width and depth).

At the same time, y (the height or length, I suppose) is usually shorter than other two dimensions

  1. Compare and contrast coord_cartesian() vs xlim() or ylim() when zooming in on a histogram. What happens if you leave binwidth unset? What happens if you try and zoom so only half a bar shows?

coord_cartesian() sets the limits on the coordinate system performs a visual zoom. The data is unchanged. Smooth continues past the points visible on the plot. Args: - xlim, ylim - expand = TRUE, default (coordinate system) = FALSE - clip = on (if off, points may be appear outside the plot)

Setting the limits on a scale converts all values outside the range to NA. es scale_x_continuous(limits = c(325, 500)) is equivalent to call xlim() and ylim(functions) When zooming the scale, the we get 25 new bins that are the same, size on the plot, but represent smaller regions of the data space.

When zooming the coordinate system, we see a subset of original 50 bins, displayed bigger

  1. What variable in the diamonds dataset is most important for predicting the price of a diamond? How is that variable correlated with cut? Why does the combination of those two relationships lead to lower quality diamonds being more expensive?

First of all, we try to plot. I chose a bin2d since its a sort of bidimensional histogram to plot those two varabiables. Geom_point does not represent well data, with strong vertical bars where carat threasholds are in place.

ggplot(fdiamonds, aes(carat, price)) +
  geom_bin2d() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

To compare carat-cut distributions, we plot them side to side. Histogram has not been used since distributions greatly differ in number of diamonds.

ggplot(fdiamonds) +
  geom_density( aes(carat, fill = cut) ,
                show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap( ~cut )

As we can see there is a strong binding between the two variable, where fair diamonds seem to be with more carats. More specifically, distributions greatly differ from one another.

Q: Why does the combination of those two relationships lead to lower quality
diamonds being more expensive?
We can see that price increases with carat, but also a higher quality is more difficult to achieve. So, most "ideal" diamonds are low-carat, while a greater number of worse cut diamonds are high-carat. Those two conflicting trends create the bias with lower quality diamonds are more expensive.

No difference can be seen from data, they are equivalent expressions

  1. One problem with boxplots is that they were developed in an era of much smaller datasets and tend to display a prohibitively large number of outlying values. One approach to remedy this problem is the letter value plot. Install the lvplot package, and try using geom_lv() to display the distribution of price vs cut. What do you learn? How do you interpret the plots?
library(lvplot)

ggplot(fdiamonds) +
  geom_lv( aes(cut, price,
               fill = cut)) +
  geom_boxplot( aes(cut, price),
                alpha = 0.05)

Fattest box is between letter values that are (approximate) quartiles, next till 8-tiles, then 16-tiles and so on. Letter stops when confidence intervals overlap with next letter, leaving outliers from then on.

Regarding interpreation, eache box represent as many data points as the sum of all subsequent ones.

  1. Compare and contrast geom_violin() with a facetted geom_histogram(), or a coloured geom_freqpoly(). What are the pros and cons of each method?
ggplot(fdiamonds, aes(x = price, y = color, fill = color)) +
  geom_violin()

Pros: - easily compare really different distributions - works also if they have different count (uses the density function)

Cons: - the more categories, the more difficult the plot is to interpret

ggplot(fdiamonds, aes(x = price, fill = color)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap( ~color )
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Pros: - useful even with a lot of categories - very easy to compare if they have similar count number

Cons: - density function is not standard - small difference cannot be seen if the plot are not stacked over each other

ggplot(fdiamonds, aes(x = price, 
                      y = ..density.., 
                      color = color)) +
  geom_freqpoly()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Pros: - easy to compare small differences

Cons: - the more categories, the more difficult to read is the plot - the more similar are distributions, the same

  1. Use geom_tile() together with dplyr to explore how average flight delays vary by destination and month of year. What makes the plot difficult to read? How could you improve it?
nycflights13::flights %>% 
  group_by(dest, month) %>% 
  summarize( avg_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_tile( aes( x = dest,
                    y = month,
                    fill = avg_delay))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'dest'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

The plot is difficult to read because: - x and y are switched - data bars are stretched - destination are ordered according to the alphabet - blue shades are not informative

We should: - switch x and y - fix coordinates (facet the wrap to allow easier reading) - order from the worst to the best - choose better color palette

nycflights13::flights %>% 
  group_by(dest, month) %>% 
  summarize( avg_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate( dest_delay = mean(avg_delay)) %>%
  filter( dest != "LGA") %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_tile( aes( x = month,
                    y = reorder(dest, avg_delay),
                    fill = avg_delay)) +
    facet_wrap( ~ dest_delay < median(dest_delay),
                scales = "free_y") +
    scale_fill_gradient(low="yellow", high="red")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'dest'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

  1. Why is it slightly better to use aes(x = color, y = cut) rather than aes(x = cut, y = color) in the example above?

Because more unique values (especially if text) are easier to read on the y-axis so they have no rotation.

  1. How does the price distribution of very large diamonds compare to small diamonds? Is it as you expect, or does it surprise you?

As we can see, lowest quintile is way less stretched than the bigger one (which is also obviously more expensive), variance increases with carats probably because quality on other features can play a bigger role.

  1. Two dimensional plots reveal outliers that are not visible in one dimensional plots. For example, some points in the plot below have an unusual combination of x and y values, which makes the points outliers even though their x and y values appear normal when examined separately.
ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(4, 11), ylim = c(4, 11))

Why is a scatterplot a better display than a binned plot for this case?

Because we want to be sure that each outlier can be identified.
